value.value: A membrane-bounded intracellular vesicle formed by maturation of an early phagosome following the ingestion of particulate material by phagocytosis; during maturation, phagosomes acquire markers of late endosomes and lysosomes.
An intracellular signaling cassette in which a small monomeric GTPase of the ARF subfamily relays a signal.

label.value: regulation of ARF protein signal transduction

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of ARF protein signal transduction.

label.value: negative regulation of ARF protein signal transduction

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of ARF protein signal transduction.

label.value: positive regulation of ARF protein signal transduction

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of ARF protein signal transduction.
Catalysis of the reaction: 2-methylbutanol + NADP+ = 2-methylbutanal + NADPH + H+.
A prominent mass in the cytoplasm of previtellogenic oocytes. The cloud contains both mitochondria and electron-dense granulofibrillar material (GFM) and is the source of germinal granule material.
The covalent addition to a protein of ISG15, a ubiquitin-like protein.
A complex of five proteins, designated NELF-A, -B, -C, -D, and -E in human, that can physically associate with RNP polymerase II to induce transcriptional pausing.
The proteolytic processing of trypsinogen to the active form, trypsin.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cobalt ion (Co2+) stimulus.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a magnesium ion stimulus.
Binding to a light chain of a myosin complex.
Binding to the head/neck region of a myosin heavy chain.
Binding to the tail region of a myosin heavy chain.
Binding to a light chain of a myosin I complex.
Binding to the head/neck region of a myosin I heavy chain.
Binding to the tail region of a myosin I heavy chain.
Binding to a light chain of a myosin II complex.
Binding to the head/neck region of a myosin II heavy chain.
Binding to the tail region of a myosin II heavy chain.
Binding to a heavy chain of a myosin complex.
Binding to a heavy chain of a myosin I complex.
Binding to a heavy chain of a myosin II complex.
A protein complex that stably associates with the C-terminus of RNA polymerase II and mediates 3'-end processing of small nuclear RNAs generated by RNA polymerase II.

A large ribonucleoprotein complex that is an early preribosomal complex. In S. cerevisiae, it has a size of 80S and consists of the 35S pre-rRNA, early-associating ribosomal proteins most of which are part of the small ribosomal subunit, the U3 snoRNA and associated proteins.

Catalysis of the reaction: histone H3 N6-acetyl-L-lysine (position 14) + H2O = histone H3 L-lysine (position 14) + acetate. This reaction requires the presence of NAD, and represents the removal of an acetyl group from lysine at position 14 of the histone H3 protein.
The chemical reactions and pathways involving mitochondrial DNA.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of mitochondrial DNA.

A heterodimeric protein complex formed of Spt4 and Spt5 proteins which is expressed in eukaryotes from yeast to man. DSIF is an inhibitory elongation factor that promotes RNA polymerase II transcriptional pausing, but can also stimulate transcriptional elongation under certain conditions, and may play a role in RNA processing via its physical association with mRNA capping enzymes.
A protein complex that stimulates the exchange of guanyl nucleotides associated with a GTPase.

A membrane-bounded flattened sac that is formed during micropexophagy between the membrane tips of an engulfing vacuole, completing the engulfment and sequestration of peroxisomes from the cytosol, and forming a micropexophagic body within the lumen of the vacuole.

A double-membrane-bounded organelle that functions in iron-sulfur protein maturation; evolutionarily derived from mitochondria. The mitosome has been detected only in anaerobic or microaerophilic organisms that do not have mitochondria, such as Entamoeba histolytica, Giardia intestinalis and several species of Microsporidia. These organisms are not capable of gaining energy from oxidative phosphorylation, which is normally performed by mitochondria.

definition.value: In Giardia species, mitosomes are sometimes present between the two nuclei.

value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways involving cardiolipin, 1,3-bis(3-phosphatidyl)glycerol.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of cardiolipin, 1,3-bis(3-phosphatidyl)glycerol.
Binding to a clathrin heavy chain.
Binding to a clathrin light chain.
Binding to a bile acid, a steroid carboxylic acids occurring in bile.

A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a ciliary basal body, a short cylindrical array of microtubules and associated proteins found at the base of a eukaryotic cilium (also called flagellum).

label.value: negative regulation of translation in response to stress

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate of translation as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress.

label.value: positive regulation of translation in response to stress

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of translation as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress.

label.value: negative regulation of translational initiation in response to stress

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate of translation initiation as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress.

label.value: positive regulation of translational initiation in response to stress

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of translation initiation as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress.

A cell extension caused by localized decoupling of the cytoskeleton from the plasma membrane and characterized by rapid formation, rounded shape, and scarcity of organelles within the protrusion. Blebs are formed during apoptosis and other cellular processes, including cell locomotion, cell division, and as a result of physical or chemical stresses.

The assembly of a bleb, a cell extension caused by localized decoupling of the cytoskeleton from the plasma membrane and characterized by rapid formation, rounded shape, and scarcity of organelles within the protrusion. Plasma membrane blebbing occurs during apoptosis and other cellular processes, including cell locomotion, cell division, and as a result of physical or chemical stresses.

label.value: negative regulation of translation in response to osmotic stress

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate of translation as a result of a stimulus indicating an increase or decrease in the concentration of solutes outside the organism or cell.

label.value: positive regulation of translation in response to osmotic stress

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of translation as a result of a stimulus indicating an increase or decrease in the concentration of solutes outside the organism or cell.

label.value: negative regulation of translational initiation in response to osmotic stress

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate of translation initiation, as a result of a stimulus indicating an increase or decrease in the concentration of solutes outside the organism or cell.

label.value: positive regulation of translational initiation in response to osmotic stress
